<!-- About the Teacher Section -->
<section id="about-teacher" class="section" data-scroll>
    <div class="section-accent-top" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="about-teacher-container">
        
        <!-- Section 1: Introduction -->
        <article class="about-teacher-block about-teacher-block-1" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-text-wrapper">
                <div class="about-teacher-section">
                    <h2 class="about-teacher-heading">I sit with the silence first</h2>
                    <p>
                        I didn't come to the bansuri seeking mastery. I came because something in me needed to slow down—to breathe differently, to listen differently. The flute taught me that lesson before it taught me anything about sound.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For the last decade, I've been doing this work. Not to collect students or build a reputation, but because I believe this practice—this way of being with the breath—matters. It steadies you. It gives you back your own rhythm.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        When you come to me, that's what I'm here for: to help you find that same quiet foundation. Everything else follows from there.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-teacher-image-wrapper">
                <img src="images/kuldeep2.jpeg"
                     alt="Kuldeep Mishra practicing in stillness"
                     class="about-teacher-image" />
            </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Section 2: Why Bansuri -->
        <article class="about-teacher-block about-teacher-block-2" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-image-wrapper">
                <img src="images/kuldeep1.jpeg"
                     alt="The bansuri in traditional learning"
                     class="about-teacher-image" />
            </div>
            <div class="about-teacher-text-wrapper">
                <div class="about-teacher-section">
                    <h2 class="about-teacher-heading">Why this instrument matters</h2>
                    <p>
                        The bansuri asks you to do something modern life rarely allows: stop, breathe, and listen to the spaces between sound.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        There's no way to fake it. No technique that works without presence. Your breath is the sound—so the breath must be steady, patient, aware. That alone changes something in you.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In a world that rewards speed, this practice moves slowly. Intentionally. And that slowness is exactly what many people need most right now.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Section 3: My Guru -->
        <article class="about-teacher-block about-teacher-block-3" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-text-wrapper">
                <div class="about-teacher-section">
                    <h2 class="about-teacher-heading">What my teacher taught me</h2>
                    <p>
                        I trained under a guru who embodied patience. He never rushed a single note. He would let me sit with one phrase for weeks, then months, until something shifted in my listening. Not because I was slow, but because real learning doesn't happen quickly.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        He taught me that discipline isn't harsh. It's gentle. It's showing up, again and again, with the same care. He taught me that listening matters more than playing. That humility opens doors that ego closes.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I carry that into my own teaching. Not as rules, but as a quiet understanding: this practice is a conversation between you, the breath, and the silence.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-teacher-image-wrapper">
                <img src="images/kuldeep3.jpeg"
                     alt="The tradition of one-on-one learning"
                     class="about-teacher-image about-teacher-image-soft" />
            </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Section 4: Teaching Philosophy -->
        <article class="about-teacher-block about-teacher-block-4" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-image-wrapper">
                <img src="images/kuldeep2.jpeg"
                     alt="Teaching as presence and care"
                     class="about-teacher-image" />
            </div>
            <div class="about-teacher-text-wrapper">
                <div class="about-teacher-section">
                    <h2 class="about-teacher-heading">How learning happens here</h2>
                    <p>
                        I don't teach a system. I teach a presence. Here's what that means:
                    </p>
                    <ul class="about-teacher-philosophy-list">
                        <li><strong>Breath first.</strong> We stabilize the breath before worrying about notes.</li>
                        <li><strong>No force.</strong> If it feels tense, we pause and recalibrate.</li>
                        <li><strong>Your pace.</strong> Some days are for building. Some are for resting. Both matter.</li>
                        <li><strong>Listening is the practice.</strong> To yourself, to the silence, to the space between sounds.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>
                        There's no pressure to progress fast. There's only the invitation to deepen—in your own time, at your own rhythm.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Section 5: My Future Plan -->
        <article class="about-teacher-block about-teacher-block-5" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-text-wrapper">
                <div class="about-teacher-section">
                    <h2 class="about-teacher-heading">What matters to me going forward</h2>
                    <p>
                        I'm not interested in teaching hundreds of students. I'm interested in teaching deeply—staying long enough with each person to see them truly shift.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This work is about preserving a way of learning that's almost extinct. One-on-one. Patient. Unrushed. Where a guru doesn't lecture but sits with you, watching your breath, your fingers, your mind. That's what I want to protect.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        My commitment is simple: to be here, fully present, for whoever is serious about this practice. To hold space for the silence. To remind you, again and again, that slow is not slow—it's the only real speed.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-teacher-image-wrapper">
                <img src="images/kuldeep1.jpeg"
                     alt="Dedicated to traditional learning"
                     class="about-teacher-image" />
            </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Section 6: Closing Reflection -->
        <article class="about-teacher-closing" data-scroll-item>
            <div class="about-teacher-closing-content">
                <p>
                    If this way of being with the bansuri resonates with you—if you're drawn to slowness, to breath, to the kind of learning that changes you quietly—then we can begin.
                </p>
                <div class="about-teacher-cta-wrapper">
                    <a href="https://calendar.app.google/iew7hQRcnT1rQyse7" class="cta cta-about" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                        Begin with a First Session
                    </a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </article>

    </div>
    <div class="section-accent-bottom" aria-hidden="true"></div>
</section>

